  "doc_id": "40161",
  "text": "In this issue of Circulation, Mauri et al [CITATION_1] examine the 2-year outcomes of patients treated with DES or BMS in the year when DES were introduced to the market and both stent types were used widely. In the period 2003 to 2004 in the State of Massachusetts, all patients who were residents of the state and received DES or BMS exclusively were followed. The mandatory data entry and the ability to link registries of vital statistics and death index to the Massachusetts registry of percutaneous coronary intervention cases enabled longitudinal follow-up. After matching to control for differences in patient and procedure characteristics, these investigators found a significantly better 2-year survival rate among the patients treated with DES compared to those treated with BMS (mortality 9.8% for DES and 12.0% for BMS, Pϭ0.0002).",
